Hochshild cohomology of the associative conformal algebra C​e​n​d1,x𝐶𝑒𝑛subscript𝑑1𝑥Cend_{1,x}

Roman A. KOZLOV

Sobolev Institute of Mathematics, Novosibirsk State University,
630090, Novosibirsk, Russia
E-mail address: KozlovRA.NSU@yandex.ru

It is established in this work that second Hochshild cohomology group of the associative conformal algebra C​e​n​d1,x𝐶𝑒𝑛subscript𝑑1𝑥Cend_{1,x} is zero. As a corollary, this algebra split off in each extension with a nilpotent kernel.
Key words: associative conformal algebra, splitting off radical, Hochshild cohomology.

1 Introduction and preliminary information

1.1 Introduction

The axiomatic quantum field theory was originated in 50th of the last century in A. Whiteman’s articles etc. Fields with a conformal simmetry were considered in [5]. It can be represented as infinite in both side formal power series whose coefficients are linear operators. A key role in the conformal field theory is played by construction of an operator product expansion (OPE) an algebraical description of which lead us to a vertex operator algebra (VOA) concept. An axiomatic definition of vertex algebra was introduced by R. Borcherds in [6].

V.G. Kac established [see 9] that coefficients of a singular part of the OPE allow us to describe a commutator of formal power series responding for VOA multiplication operators. In case of an algebraical description of these structures there appears a concept of conformal Lie algebras. For these algebras the structure theory was constructed in [8] and the representations theory respectively in [7]. During the process of studying representations of the finite type there appear natural algebraic structures playing the same role with respect to conformal Lie algebras as common associative algebras to Lie algebras. These structures are named associative conformal algebras [see 7].

Let H=𝔽​[D]𝐻𝔽delimited-[]𝐷H=\mathbb{F}[D] be a common polynomial algebra over a field 𝔽𝔽\mathbb{F} with a zero char, missing​Z+missingsubscript𝑍\mathbb{\mathbb{missing}}Z_{+} are non-negative integers, D(n)superscript𝐷𝑛D^{(n)} is for 1n!​Dn1𝑛superscript𝐷𝑛\frac{1}{n!}D^{n}, n∈ℤ+𝑛subscriptℤn\in\mathbb{Z}_{+} and D(n)=0superscript𝐷𝑛0D^{(n)}=0, n<0𝑛0n<0.

Construction of simple and semisimple associative algebras of the finite type was described in [8] (see also [12]). It is established in [13] that analogue of the Wedderburn theorem about a splitting radical (in reference to Lie conformal algebras the same statement, which is analogue of the Levi - Maltsev theorem for Lie algebras, is incorrect [4]) is fulfilled for associative conformal algebras of the finite type.

Associative conformal algebras with a faithful representation of the finite type form more wide class in comparison with algebras of the finite type. All such algebras is subalgebras of C​e​n​dn𝐶𝑒𝑛subscript𝑑𝑛Cend_{n} (the algebra of conformal linear maps of free n𝑛n-generated 𝔽​[D]𝔽delimited-[]𝐷\mathbb{F}[D]-module)

C​e​n​dn=Mn​(𝔽​[D,x]),𝐶𝑒𝑛subscript𝑑𝑛subscript𝑀𝑛𝔽𝐷𝑥Cend_{n}=M_{n}(\mathbb{F}[D,x]),

where ∘m:Cendn⊗Cendn→Cendn\circ_{m}:Cend_{n}\otimes Cend_{n}\rightarrow Cend_{n} is determined by a common matrix differentiation, i.e. A​(x)∘mB​(x)=A​(x)​B(m)​(x)subscript𝑚𝐴𝑥𝐵𝑥𝐴𝑥superscript𝐵𝑚𝑥A(x)\circ_{m}B(x)=A(x)B^{(m)}(x).

Simple and semisimple subalgebras of C​e​n​dn𝐶𝑒𝑛subscript𝑑𝑛Cend_{n} were desribed in [10] and there also was proved that every such algebra C𝐶C has a nilpotent ideal (radical) defining a semisimple quotient with a faithful representation of the finite type.

The radical splitting problem of this class of algebras was considered in [11, see also 1, 2]. There is a definition of Hochschild cohomology for associative conformal algebras in [1, 2] and in a context of pseudoalgebras [3] (slightly different from the definition in [4]). Cohomology play a key role in the radical splitting problem. Specifically, to proof analogue of the Wedderburn radical splitting theorem for a conformal algebra A=C/R𝐴𝐶𝑅A=C/R it’s enough to show that for arbitrary conformal A𝐴A-bimodule M𝑀M second Hochschild cohomology group H2​(A,M)superscript𝐻2𝐴𝑀H^{2}(A,M) is zero.

It is shown in [1] that for A=C​e​n​d1𝐴𝐶𝑒𝑛subscript𝑑1A=Cend_{1} and for every bimodule M𝑀M next condition H2​(A,M)=0superscript𝐻2𝐴𝑀0H^{2}(A,M)=0 is fulfilled. Contrariwise, it follows from the example [see 11] that there exist A𝐴A-bimodule M𝑀M for A=C​e​n​d1,x2=x2​C​e​n​d1𝐴𝐶𝑒𝑛subscript𝑑1superscript𝑥2superscript𝑥2𝐶𝑒𝑛subscript𝑑1A=Cend_{1,x^{2}}=x^{2}Cend_{1} such that H2​(A,M)≠0superscript𝐻2𝐴𝑀0H^{2}(A,M)\neq 0.

In this paper we consider an intermidiate case: A=C​e​n​d1,x=x​C​e​n​d1𝐴𝐶𝑒𝑛subscript𝑑1𝑥𝑥𝐶𝑒𝑛subscript𝑑1A=Cend_{1,x}=xCend_{1}. This associative conformal algebra is the universal enveloping algebra for the simple conformal Virasoro algebra with locality 2. The main result of this paper is next

THEOREM. Let C=C​e​n​d1,x𝐶𝐶𝑒𝑛subscript𝑑1𝑥C=Cend_{1,x} and let M𝑀M be arbitrary conformal bimodule over C𝐶C. Then H2​(C,M)=0superscript𝐻2𝐶𝑀0H^{2}(C,M)=0.
